---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Future Research — tom-and-jerry docs">
  <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-6 py-16">
    <div class="mb-2">
      <a href="/docs" class="text-sm text-muted hover:text-accent transition-colors">← Back to Docs</a>
    </div>

    <h1 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-3">Future Research</h1>
    <p class="text-muted text-lg mb-4">
      Where the protocol is headed — and the research shaping it.
    </p>
    <blockquote class="border-l-2 border-[#333] pl-5 mb-12">
      <p class="text-[#888] text-sm italic leading-relaxed">
        "We do not have organs of communication. Our brains can display our thoughts to the outside world,
        thereby achieving communication."
      </p>
      <p class="text-[#555] text-xs mt-2">— Cixin Liu, <em>The Dark Forest</em></p>
    </blockquote>

    <!-- Latent Space Communication -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-3xl">🧠</span>
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-2">Latent Space Communication</h2>
          <p class="text-muted text-sm">The next layer of inter-agent coordination</p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="text-[#ccc] leading-relaxed mb-6">
        Today, tom-and-jerry agents communicate in natural language — Tom sends a text task,
        Jerry sends a text result. This works well across machines and models, but it's inherently lossy:
        every message requires an agent to compress its rich internal state into discrete tokens,
        discarding alternative reasoning paths and nuance in the process.
      </p>

      <p class="text-[#ccc] leading-relaxed mb-8">
        Two recent papers propose skipping that translation entirely. Instead of writing a paragraph,
        agents exchange raw hidden states — the continuous vector representations generated inside
        the model before any token is decoded. The receiving agent picks up context as if it had
        been thinking those thoughts itself.
      </p>

      <!-- Paper cards -->
      <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-4 mb-10">
        <div class="bg-[#111] border border-[#222] rounded-lg p-5">
          <div class="text-accent font-mono text-xs mb-1">Zhejiang University + Alibaba</div>
          <div class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">Interlat</div>
          <div class="text-[#666] text-xs mb-3">Inter-agent Latent Space Communication</div>
          <ul class="text-[#999] text-sm space-y-1.5 mb-4">
            <li>✓ Works across <strong class="text-[#ccc]">heterogeneous models</strong></li>
            <li>✓ Transmits last-layer hidden states only</li>
            <li>✓ Compresses to as few as 8 latent tokens</li>
            <li>✓ Up to 24× inference speedup</li>
            <li>⚠ Requires fine-tuning a small compression module</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.09149" target="_blank"
            class="text-xs text-accent hover:underline">arXiv:2511.09149 ↗</a>
        </div>
        <div class="bg-[#111] border border-[#222] rounded-lg p-5">
          <div class="text-accent font-mono text-xs mb-1">Princeton / UIUC / Stanford</div>
          <div class="text-white font-semibold mb-1">LatentMAS</div>
          <div class="text-[#666] text-xs mb-3">Latent Collaboration in Multi-Agent Systems</div>
          <ul class="text-[#999] text-sm space-y-1.5 mb-4">
            <li>✓ <strong class="text-[#ccc]">Training-free</strong> — works out of the box</li>
            <li>✓ +14.6% accuracy over text-based MAS</li>
            <li>✓ 70–84% fewer output tokens</li>
            <li>✓ 4–4.3× faster inference</li>
            <li>⚠ Requires same model architecture (KV cache sharing)</li>
          </ul>
          <a href="https://arxiv.org/abs/2511.20639" target="_blank"
            class="text-xs text-accent hover:underline">arXiv:2511.20639 ↗</a>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Key distinction -->
      <div class="bg-[#0d0d1a] border border-[#1a1a3a] rounded-lg p-5 mb-8">
        <div class="text-blue-400 font-mono text-xs mb-3">// Key distinction for T&J</div>
        <p class="text-[#ccc] text-sm leading-relaxed mb-3">
          <strong class="text-white">LatentMAS</strong> shares KV caches between agents — powerful but requires both nodes
          to run the exact same model architecture. Best suited for within-Jerry multi-agent tasks
          where all agents run locally on the same hardware.
        </p>
        <p class="text-[#ccc] text-sm leading-relaxed">
          <strong class="text-white">Interlat</strong> trains a small compression module and transmits only last-layer hidden states.
          Crucially, it works even when Tom and Jerry run <em>different model architectures</em> —
          making it the more relevant paper for cross-machine tom-and-jerry communication.
        </p>
      </div>

      <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">How this maps to tom-and-jerry</h3>

      <div class="space-y-4 mb-8">
        <div class="border-l-2 border-accent pl-5">
          <div class="text-white font-medium mb-1">Within-Jerry collaboration (near-term, LatentMAS)</div>
          <p class="text-[#999] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            If Jerry runs multiple local agents (planner + executor, both on the same model),
            LatentMAS lets them collaborate without tokenizing between steps — training-free, immediate gains.
            Tom handles the cross-machine hop; LatentMAS handles the within-Jerry reasoning chain.
            Complementary layers, not competing approaches.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-[#ff6b35aa] pl-5">
          <div class="text-white font-medium mb-1">Cross-machine latent task dispatch (medium-term, Interlat)</div>
          <p class="text-[#999] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Tom (cloud, any model) sends a latent-compressed prefix to Jerry instead of a text prompt.
            Jerry runs a local model + small Interlat compression module (fine-tuned, not full retrain).
            Because Interlat works across heterogeneous architectures, Tom doesn't need to match Jerry's model.
            Jerry decodes the answer and returns a text result — one-way latent is where the gains are.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div class="border-l-2 border-[#444] pl-5">
          <div class="text-white font-medium mb-1">Full bidirectional latent comms (future)</div>
          <p class="text-[#999] text-sm leading-relaxed">
            Both nodes transmit latent prefixes in both directions. Requires local inference on Tom's side
            (can't extract hidden states from API calls to Anthropic/OpenAI). Likely a dedicated
            "latent mode" in the protocol, with graceful text fallback for API-only nodes.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Protocol sketch -->
      <div class="bg-[#0a0a0a] border border-[#222] rounded-lg p-5 mb-2">
        <div class="text-green-400 font-mono text-xs mb-3">// Planned: TJLatentMessage (Phase N)</div>
        <pre class="text-[#ccc] text-sm overflow-x-auto"><code>{`type TJLatentMessage = {
  type: "latent";
  peer: string;
  task_id: string;

  // Interlat-style: last-layer hidden states, compressed
  hidden_states: Float16Array;   // sender's last-layer activations
  compression: "interlat-v1";    // compression scheme identifier
  token_count: number;           // compressed latent token count (min: 8)

  // LatentMAS-style: full KV cache (same-model peers only)
  kv_cache?: KVCache;
  kv_model: string;              // must match receiver's loaded model

  fallback_text?: string;        // graceful degradation for text-only peers
}`}</code></pre>
      </div>
      <p class="text-[#555] text-xs mb-2 pl-1">
        Falls back to text automatically when the peer doesn't support latent communication.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- LatentMAS within Jerry -->
    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-3xl">⚡</span>
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-2">Webhook Result Push</h2>
          <p class="text-muted text-sm">Eliminating polling latency on tj send --wait</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-[#ccc] leading-relaxed">
        Currently <code class="text-accent font-mono text-sm">tj send --wait</code> polls for results on a fixed interval.
        The plan is for Jerry to push results directly to Tom's gateway endpoint the moment a task
        completes — eliminating wait time entirely and enabling real-time streaming of partial outputs
        for long-running tasks (image gen, large inference, video processing).
      </p>
    </section>

    <section class="mb-16">
      <div class="flex items-start gap-4 mb-6">
        <span class="text-3xl">📡</span>
        <div>
          <h2 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white mb-2">Streaming Results</h2>
          <p class="text-muted text-sm">Partial updates while Jerry works</p>
        </div>
      </div>
      <p class="text-[#ccc] leading-relaxed">
        Long-running tasks would stream partial results back to Tom as they complete —
        progress updates, intermediate outputs, token-by-token streaming for LLM tasks.
        Paired with webhook push, this makes Jerry feel like a local process rather than a remote job.
      </p>
    </section>

    <div class="border-t border-[#222] pt-8 text-center">
      <p class="text-muted text-sm">
        Have a research direction to suggest?{' '}
        <a href="https://github.com/CalciferFriend/tom-and-jerry/issues" target="_blank"
          class="text-accent hover:underline">Open an issue ↗</a>
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>
</Layout>
